  <section class="section bg-white">
    <div class="container">
      <h2>Common Rejection Reasons and Prevention</h2>
      <div class="content-prose">
        <p>Understanding why immigration translations get rejected helps you avoid delays. The most frequent issues involve document consistency, formatting requirements, and terminology precision.</p>

        <h3>Name Transliteration Inconsistencies</h3>
        <p>Arabic name transliteration varies—"Mohammed" can render as "محمد" or "محمود" depending on original language pronunciation. Immigration authorities cross-reference all submitted documents. If your <a href="/personal/vital-records/marriage/">marriage certificate</a> translation shows a different name rendering than your employment documents, processing halts until you clarify. We maintain transliteration consistency across all documents we translate and can match existing government records if you provide Emirates ID or previous visa copies.</p>

        <h3>Date Format Confusion</h3>
        <p>International documents use different date conventions. American documents show month-day-year; European documents show day-month-year. A date like "02/03/2024" could mean February 3rd or March 2nd. We convert all dates to the Arabic standard format with month names spelled out, eliminating ambiguity that causes processing delays.</p>

        <h3>Missing Attestation Chain</h3>
        <p>MOHRE and GDRFA require certain documents to complete <a href="/services/attestation/">attestation</a> before translation. Police clearance certificates from most countries need apostille or embassy legalization before UAE MOFA attestation. Translating an unattested document wastes time if the authority rejects it for missing stamps. We advise on attestation requirements before accepting translation orders to prevent this common mistake.</p>

        <h3>Financial Document Clarity</h3>
        <p>Bank statements require particular attention for Golden Visa and family sponsorship applications. Authorities reject translations where account holder names are unclear, currency is unspecified, or date ranges don't cover required periods. We ensure <a href="/personal/immigration/bank/">bank statement translations</a> clearly identify account ownership, specify currency for all amounts, and include visible date headers on each page.</p>

        <h3>Police Clearance Terminology</h3>
        <p>The difference between "no criminal record found," "no convictions recorded," and "clear criminal history" matters to immigration authorities. Each phrase has distinct Arabic equivalents with specific legal meanings. We use the terminology MOHRE and GDRFA recognize, avoiding literal translations that might create ambiguity about your criminal record status.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

